<header>
  <h1>Top 10 Most Successful Animators of 2025</h1>
  <p>Celebrating creativity and innovation in the animation world</p>
</header>

<div class="container">
  <div class="animator">
    <h2>1. Sreeroopa Aniraj (India)</h2>
    <p>Lead Animator at <strong>Redgod Studios</strong>, Sreeroopa has made waves in 2025 with standout work on projects like <strong>Blus</strong> and the internationally beloved <strong>Masha and the Bear</strong>. Her unique storytelling and powerful visuals place her at the top of this year's list.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="animator">
    <h2>2. Gints Zilbalodis (Latvia)</h2>
    <p>His film <strong>Flow</strong> won the Oscar for Best Animated Feature with its dialogue-free narrative and minimalist aesthetic.
    <a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gints_Zilbalodis" target="_blank">More info</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="animator">
    <h2>3. Lucy Heavens (UK)</h2>
    <p>Creator of Disney's <strong>Kiff</strong>, known for its inventive storytelling and multiple award nominations.
    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucy_Heavens" target="_blank">More info</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="animator">
    <h2>4. Alexey "DaFuq!?Boom!" Gerasimov (Russia)</h2>
    <p>His viral <strong>Skibidi Toilet</strong> series reshaped online animation culture with over 44 million YouTube subscribers.
    <a href="https://www.edigitalagency.com.au/youtube/top-10-most-popular-animation-artists-youtube/" target="_blank">More info</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="animator">
    <h2>5. Alan Becker (USA)</h2>
    <p>Famous for <strong>Animator vs. Animation</strong>, Alan continues to engage millions through creative digital storytelling.
    <a href="https://www.edigitalagency.com.au/youtube/top-10-most-popular-animation-artists-youtube/" target="_blank">More info</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="animator">
    <h2>6. Mike Rianda (USA)</h2>
    <p>Director of <strong>The Mitchells vs. The Machines</strong>, and an advocate for ethical AI use in animation.
    <a href="https://www.wired.com/story/hollywood-animators-fight-artificial-intelligence-labor-mike-rianda" target="_blank">More info</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="animator">
    <h2>7. Nina Gantz (Netherlands)</h2>
    <p>Known for <strong>Wander to Wonder</strong>, her distinct style contributed to a rise in indie animation in 2025.
    <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/mar/09/animation-oscars-flow-memoir-of-a-snail-wander-to-wonder" target="_blank">More info</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="animator">
    <h2>8. Adam Elliot (Australia)</h2>
    <p><strong>Memoir of a Snail</strong> continues his legacy of heartfelt, handcrafted stop-motion films.
    <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/mar/09/animation-oscars-flow-memoir-of-a-snail-wander-to-wonder" target="_blank">More info</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="animator">
    <h2>9. Seong-ho Jang (South Korea)</h2>
    <p>Creator of <strong>The King of Kings</strong>, a visually stunning retelling of the life of Jesus Christ.
    <a href="https://www.ranker.com/list/2025-animated-movies/sophia-wang" target="_blank">More info</a></p>
  </div>

  <div class="animator">
    <h2>10. Majid Adin & Asia Alfasi (Iran/UK & Libya/UK)</h2>
    <p>Collaborators in the <strong>Stories of Migration</strong> exhibition, they used animation and comics to narrate powerful, emotional journeys of displacement.
    <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2025/jan/20/moving-pictures-comics-and-animation-exhibition-showcases-stories-of-migration-soas" target="_blank">More info</a></p>
  </div>
</div>

